article.description: The Detroit Shock are having a tough time winning on their home court.
article.headline: Defending champs fall to 4-7
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock are having a tough
time winning on their home court.

The defending WNBA champions fell to 4-7 at the Palace of Auburn
Hills after losing to the Connecticut Sun 78-68 in a game played
Wednesday morning.

"The bottom line is I'm doing something wrong as a coach,"
Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "I can't seem to get our team
motivated to do little things. We've got a lot of talented players
and we're not getting it done. I'll take the blame."

The Shock have lost four of their last five, but Olympian Swin
Cash wasn't letting Laimbeer take the blame.

"I think it is us," she said. "He gives us the things we
need. We just have to go out there and execute and we aren't doing
that."

Connecticut, which finished with two wins on a five-game road
trip, is now 10-2 against the Eastern Conference.

"We just match up well with a lot of the East Coast teams, and
it gives us an advantage," said Nykesha Sales, who finished with
16 points. "This is really a big win -- it gives us the tiebreaker
against another team in our conference, and it keeps the road trip
from being a bust, which is where we were heading."

Le'Coe Willingham added 12 points for Connecticut, which only
committed four turnovers.

"We're playing with a lot of confidence right now," said Sun
coach Mike Thibault. "We've got a pretty good point guard that
doesn't turn the ball over in Lindsay Whalen."

Deanna Nolan led the Shock with 20 points, while Cash added 18.

Connecticut led 46-39 at the half behind 13 points from Sales.
The Sun led by as many as 14 points, 58-44, early in the second
half.

The Shock cut the margin with eight minutes left, but never got
closer than nine points as the teams traded baskets for most of the
half.

Taj McWilliams-Franklin, who led the Sun with 17 points, moved
past the 2,000-point mark for her career early in the second half.
